After that event there were several ups and downs, including the famous coup d’etat which has occurred in every 5 years, the leftish influenced from Gandhi and eventually in January 2012, the US-backed uprising and minus-off military coup. Now what we have in Mali is complete collapse of government and society. This is also resulting in a little rise in crime rate.

The economic situation has changed over hundred years:

Agriculture: We were dependent a lot on foreigners since we haven’t invented anything new (or even copied from others) except drawing men for digging for palm trees and poisons. This was about 50 % of our national economy, but meanwhile, rest seven decades, agriculture has come more and more into western style of farming and now we produce our own rice and chicken, goat.

Sewage-contaminated drinking water: Colonialists has taught us to throw our domestic sewage anywhere and as long as we have enough water of acceptable quality, it was ok not matter what it looks like. Basing of drinking water production took place behind those contaminated air and our drinking water was full of expelled matter. This doesn’t exist any longer since all this water-related issues has been addressed.

Roads have been installed: It is good to be able to move around and now after 1950s villages and even regions can communicate to others via roads built mostly by Force Publique.

Industries and Faculties have been installed in Urban areas.
